observations.recommendation:
Comply with the monthly submission of Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before 15th day after the end of each month; 

The Municipal Accountant maintain separate SLs for transfers of agency’s unutilized DRRMF to the STF by year of transfer, receipts of NDRRMF by transferring agency, DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU and other sources by donor; and 

Ensure henceforth, that recording of transfer of Unspent DRRMF is based on validated RAAOs for accurate presentation of balances in the financial statement.

The Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Supply Officer trace back all inventories already issued based on the Requisition and Issue Slip and Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued, and make the appropriate adjusting entries to properly account those already issued in the books of the Municipality; 

The Municipal Accountant henceforth, prepare the corresponding JEV on issuance of inventories based on the SSMI submitted by the Supply Officer to avoid accumulation of inventory accounts; and

Henceforth, require the Appraisal and Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventory items in the custody of the Supply Officer to determine undistributed/uncon-sumed items, if any, and prepare a corresponding report thereof.

Ensure submission of the lacking supporting documents as indicated in the remarks column of Table 10 to establish the validity and propriety of the transactions; 

Ensure that Office Order and letter invite (if outside personnel) are prepared as this will serve as basis in identifying the no. of pax for the quantity of meals in the PR and likewise, serves as authority of the participants to attend trainings;  

Require the MDRRMO to henceforth, secure pictures of food procured and pictures during the conduct of trainings/activity as part of the attachments to the disbursement vouchers;

Require the MSWDO to henceforth, ensure that proof of distribution and/or list of recipients are obtained for every goods distributed and that the same were completely filled out and signed by the authorized personnel/official; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursements are properly supported with complete documentation and adequate information that can establish the transactions/activities transpired, and discontinue the practice of processing payment for claims that are not sufficiently documented to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspensions or Disallowances.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Inventory and Appraisal Committee conduct physical count of all serviceable and unserviceable PPEs and ensure that RPCPPE is prepared, signed and submitted in accordance with the requirement prescribed in the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs to establish the condition and existence of the reported PPEs;
The Accounting Office and General Service Office (GSO) regather all available PPE records on file and those from other accountable officers per offices in order to identify the composition of those forwarded lump sum balances, as well as the specific description of those PPEs with insufficient details in the books to ensure that balances of PPEs appearing on the financial statements are duly supported and substantiated;
The Supply Officer determine from the PPE monitoring report of the Accounting Office those PPEs which were not yet covered with PCs and prepare and maintain the same to ensure that PPEs owned by the municipality are properly accounted, recorded and monitored;
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts by following the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020. To ensure implementation thereto, create a team or committee who shall focus on the proper execution of the aforementioned circular with a concrete timeline; and
The Municipal Accountant effect the reclassification of semi-expendable properties below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 to their appropriate expense accounts and record the cumulative effect of change in accounting policy using Prior Period Adjustment account as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Acting Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, expedite the posting of tax dues in the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s (RPTAR) index cards and update the Realty Tax Delinquency Listing as of December 31, 2024;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record the actual RPT and SET Receivable beginning balances in CY 2025 using the amounts per Realty Tax Delinquency Listing as of December 31, 2024 and to effect subsequent adjustments upon completion of updates on delinquent tax dues from the other 15 barangays;
The Acting Municipal Treasurer henceforth, prepare certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year to be provided to the Municipal Accountant; and
The Municipal Accountant set-up at the beginning of the succeeding years the RPT and SET Receivables and corresponding Deferred RPT and SET Income based on the certified list as above-mentioned.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant recognize in the book the receipt of Philhealth Fund on the month it was actually received by debiting CIB-LCCA and crediting Due to NGAs account, and those other valid reconciling items that were identified during the preparation of the BRS to enable fair presentation of the Cash in Bank-LCCA account balance;
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile the noted difference of ₱309,448.92 and effect the necessary and applicable adjustments/corrections in their respective records;
The Municipal Accountant refrain from presenting inaccurate cashbook balances in the BRS; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant ensure periodic and timely reconciliation between their records so that errors or any other reconciling items will be immediately corrected/updated.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant trace back the prior years’ journals under the TF and GF books, Summary of Receipt and Disbursements, and Utilization Reports of fund transfers received on file in order to identify the cause of the unreconciled difference in the TF book;
The Municipal Accountant exert more effort in identifying the details of the ₱171,682.00 Due to NGAs in the GF and maintain its corresponding SLs;
The Municipal Accountant prepare adjusting entries reclassifying the balances of those fund transfers from MEEDO to TF book using the Prior Year Adjustment and Due to NGAs accounts, and prepare separate SLs relative thereto;
The Municipal Treasurer trace back all prior years’ collections from building permit fees and other charges in order to compute for the five percent DPWH share and remit the same to the BTr;
The Municipal Treasurer henceforth, withhold from the collection of building permit fees and other charges the five percent DPWH share and ensure its remittance to the BTr; and
The Municipal Accountant henceforth, recognized in the books the five percent DPWH share by crediting “Due to NGAs” account in the GF book and debit the same upon remittance.

We recommend and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant immediately issue official demand to the concerned accountable officers to enforce the liquidation of the noted unliquidated cash advances;
The Municipal Accountant deduct the unliquidated cash advances of separating officials, if any, from their claim of terminal benefits by virtue of their authority to deduct;
The Municipal Accountant observe the limitation in the granting of cash advances by not allowing additional cash advances to those AO with pending/unliquidated cash advances pursuant to Section 89 of the PD 1445; and
Henceforth, ensure that all cash advances granted to any accountable officer is liquidated within the reglementary period to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and to promote timely recording in the books of accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile the noted difference of ₱33,630.14 by comparing their respective records in order to identify the cause of such difference and effect the necessary and applicable adjustments/corrections to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury account balance;
Henceforth, the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant ensure periodic and timely reconciliation between their records so that errors or any other reconciling items will be immediately corrected/updated;
The Municipal Accountant maintain the subsidiary ledgers for all bank accounts in harmony with the cashbooks maintained by the Municipal Treasurer; and
The Municipal Accountant conduct analysis of the cause of the negative or abnormal balance and locate the necessary supporting documents in order to effect necessary adjustment.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Treasurer and Accountant reconcile the noted difference of ₱39,316.49 between their records of “Cash-Local Treasury” account and effect the necessary and applicable adjustments/corrections;
The Municipal Treasurer maintain cashbook for Cash Local Treasury with DBP Acct No.  0750-009654-031;
The Municipal Accountant maintain SLs in harmony with the cashbooks of the Municipal Treasurer and to prepare and maintain SLs for each accountable officer/collecting clerks of the municipality; and
Henceforth, ensure that regular and timely reconciliation between the records of the Municipal Treasurer and Accountant is strictly observe so that errors or any other reconciling items will be immediately corrected/updated.

The Municipal Treasurer return/transfer the unutilized amount ₱1.094 million to the National Treasury as required under Section 3.8 of LBC No. 140;

The Municipal Accountant in coordination with the concerned office/department ensure that funded PPAs of the National Government are timely implemented and utilized to avoid recurrence of wasted fund opportunity for the Municipality;

The Municipal Social Welfare and Development (MSWD) Office provide sufficient evidence/supporting documents to establish that the intended recipients per payroll and DSWD form are indeed the actual recipients of the said financial assistance and the amount released to beneficiaries equates to the number of family members affected; and

The MSWD Office conduct henceforth, a thorough assessment/evaluation to beneficiaries of any financial assistance and ensure that same is sufficiently documented to guarantee responsive, equitable and effective distribution thereof and prevent any misuse of funds.

The LDRRMO prepare LDRRMFIP which shall be the basis of the MPDC in preparing the AIP and to support the release and use of LDRRMF;

The MPDC and MBO ensure henceforth, that AIP and budget records, respectively, are reconciled as the same are interrelated planning records;

The Municipal Accountant transfer the inappropriate charges of ₱10,000.00 from general fund to LDRRMF and stop the charging from LDRRMF of expenses that are administrative in nature and are not directly related to disaster risk reduction and management activities, otherwise, it shall be disallowed in audit;

The Supply Officer ensure that pictures taken for each procurement can be identified and quantified with the items procured based on the Purchase Order;

The MSWD Office ensure that RDSs are completely filled out and signed by authorized personnel/official;

The Municipal Accountant ensure that all LDRRMF utilizations were supported with LDDRMFIP and AIP/Supplemental AIP, respectively, and with appropriate funding source;

The LDRRMO and MPDC exercise prudence in preparing LDRRMFIP and AIP/Supplemental AIP, respectively;

The LDRRMO and MPDC be reminded that the LDRRMFIP and AIP are interrelated planning records, hence, they should be prepared in relation to the other and must supply coherent/consistent information for more effective and efficient planning and be prepared in such a way not to confuse readers or stakeholders; and

The Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer prepare the monthly Report on the Receipt and Utilization of DRRM Sourced from GAA and ensure its timely submission on the 5th day following the end of each month to the concerned offices.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
Re-evaluate the PPAs under continuing appropriations and cause the reversion or re-alignment of the appropriated funds for PPAs no longer needed or necessary so that same may be used effectively and efficiently for more appropriate priority development projects;
The Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer regularly monitor all the programs and projects of the municipality and submit a monitoring report as basis to issue memorandum to the implementing office to ensure full implementation of the development projects;
Ensure that the development projects funded under the 20% Development Fund comply with the guidelines set forth in the DBM-DOF-DILG JMC 2020-1 dated November 4, 2020 and optimally contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the Municipality; and
Identify the specific developmental projects under Various Barangay Projects appropriation to better evaluate its eligibility under 20% Development Fund.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The MPDC prepare a Supplemental AIP for CY 2021 incorporating the procurement of rescue vehicle to be charged from STF;
The Municipal Accountant obligate transactions by preparing accounting entry recognizing the payable account for those transactions that have occurred and budgeted/funded on the same year so as to avoid disbursements with no corresponding fund or budget;
The Municipal Accountant prepare adjusting entry reclassifying the Motor Vehicle account to Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment account and its corresponding Accumulated Depreciation account; and
The Municipal Accountant comply with the guidelines set forth in JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 in accounting for procurement of Disaster Equipment for Disaster Response and Rescue Activities.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The LDRRMO prepare LDRRMFIP to support the release and use of LDRRMF and as basis by the MPDC for inclusion in the AIP;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that all LDRRMF utilizations were supported with LDDRMFIP and AIP/Supplemental AIP, respectively, and with appropriate funding source;
The LDRRMO and MPDC exercise prudence in preparing LDDRMFIP and AIP/Supplemental AIP, respectively;
The LDRRMO and MPDC be reminded that the LDRRMFIP and AIP are interrelated planning records, hence, they should be prepared in relation to the other and must supply coherent/consistent information for more effective and efficient planning and be prepared in such a way not to confuse readers or stakeholders; and
The LDRRMO and Municipal Accountant submit the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization on DRRMF on or before the 15th day of each month as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:

The Municipal Accountant observe the perpetual inventory system in the recording/maintaining of inventory accounts and corresponding issuance thereof;

The Supply Officer prepare the SSMI and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant weekly for proper accounting of issuance of inventories, and conduct year-end physical count of inventory items, in coordination with the MSWDO, to determine the undistributed/unconsumed items, if any, and the cost of these items shall be restored back to the inventory account;

Provide for a designated stock room to properly store and secure the relief goods in stocks of the municipality; and

The MSWDO observe the following: 

Require the concerned personnel to reconcile the summary list of beneficiaries with the actual RDSs; have the signature of the 183 recipients to acknowledge their receipt of the relief goods; and have the RDSs be duly signed by the concerned/in-charge officials;

Henceforth, ensure that all RDSs were fully filled out and duly signed to provide sufficient and reliable information and promote transparency especially on the items and quantity of the relief goods distributed to the beneficiaries; and

Maintain a registry per article/item of goods to monitor/track its issuance and balances and to prepare and maintain a separate logbook to record the receipt and distribution of relief goods per sources of funds.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:

The LDRRMO prepare LDRRMFIP to support the release and use of LDRRMF;

The OIC-Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer prepare the monthly Report on the Receipt and Utilization of DRRM Sourced from GAA and ensure its timely submission on the 5th day following the end of each month to the concerned offices;

The LDRRMO, Budget and Accounting Office reconcile and determine the unexpended/obligated balance of the LDRRMF for CO that should be made continuing in the General Fund books and the correct amount of unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and LDRRMF-MOOE that should be transferred to the Special Trust Fund;

The LDRRMO and OIC-Municipal Accountant prepare and submit the monthly Report on Utilization of DRRMF on or before 15th day after the end of each month and ensure that the corrected amounts were provided in the report; and

The OIC-Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursements from LDRRMF are duly supported with LDRRMFIP.

We recommended the following:

Continually look for suitable site for a sanitary landfill that will be developed and operated as a final disposal site for solid and, eventually, residual wastes of the municipality in compliance with the Solid Waste Management Act;


Observe the necessary control measures in the operation of the current disposal site in accordance with RA 9003 to avoid adverse impact to the environment. Prioritize the installation of a Materials Recovery Facility in the site and the segregation of the existing solid wastes therein for proper processing; 

After finalizing the planned adaptation of the Alternative Technology, expedite its implementation to avoid congestion of unprocessed residual wastes in the dumping site;



Intensify the Information, Education and Communication campaign to its stakeholders on waste reduction and proper waste segregation and strictly impose and enforce the fines and penalties for violators; and

Materials Recovery Facility be established in every barangay or cluster of barangays. The municipality may initially pilot a single barangay to establish MRF project in order to institute a system of knowledge in establishing one as well as to gain commitment/participation of barangay officials on the proper administration and the operation of MRF.

We recommended that the Management:

Cause the immediate implementation of the development projects in accordance with the guidelines set forth in the DILG-DBM Joint MC 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017;

The Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Planning and Development Council (MPDC) to regularly monitor all the programs and projects of the municipality and submit a monitoring report as basis for the former to issue memorandum to the implementing office to ensure full implementation of the development projects.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Assessor to furnish the Municipal Treasurer on or before the thirty-first (31st) day of December of each year, an assessment roll containing a list of all real property, whether taxable or exempt, located within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipality and a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;
The Municipal Treasurer to regularly update the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Tax Payers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year-end; and to prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts. In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;
The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to conduct reconciliation of  records based on the index card balances  so that necessary adjustments could be made to bring the affected receivable and deferred accounts to its correct balance;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT/SET Receivables based on the certified list of taxpayers and its corresponding amount due and collectibles from the Municipal Treasurer; and
The Local Chief Executive (LCE), Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Municipal Officials to exert concerted efforts to intensify collections of long outstanding RPT and SET Receivables including the interest thereon so that more development programs may be implemented for the benefit of the constituents.

We recommended the following:

Continually look for suitable site for a sanitary landfill that will be developed and operated as a final disposal site for solid and, eventually, residual wastes of the municipality in compliance with the Solid Waste Management Act;

Observe the necessary control measures in the operation of the current disposal site in accordance with RA 9003 to avoid adverse impact to the environment. Prioritize the installation of a Materials Recovery Facility in the site and the segregation of the existing solid wastes therein for proper processing; 



After finalizing the planned adaptation of the Alternative Technology, expedite its implementation to avoid congestion of unprocessed residual wastes in the dumping site;


The solid wastes containers should be properly and visibly labeled as to biodegradable, non-biodegradable, recyclable, special waste and other waste classification in the strategic places of the municipality;

Segregated waste collections be maintained. Considering that the municipality is using sacks for collecting solid wastes, they should be utilized in such a way that one sack will be used for one solid waste classification and the other for another classification and correspondingly labeled in order to avoid the melding of all solid wastes and easy segregation as well as ready recovery in the dumping site; 	

Intensify the Information, Education and Communication campaign to its stakeholders on waste reduction and proper waste segregation and strictly impose and enforce the fines and penalties for violators; and

Materials Recovery Facility be established in every barangay or cluster of barangays.  The municipality may initially pilot a single barangay to establish MRF project in order to institute a system of knowledge in establishing one as well as to gain commitment/participation of barangay officials on the proper administration and the operation of MRF.

We recommended that the Management:

a. Cause the immediate implementation of the development projects in accordance with the guidelines set forth in the DILG-DBM Joint MC 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017;

b. The Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Planning and Development Council (MPDC) to regularly monitor all the programs and projects of the municipality and submit a monitoring report as basis for the former to issue memorandum to the implementing office to ensure full implementation of the development projects.

We recommended that the present Municipal Agriculturist formulate the implementing guidelines for the granting of any financial/technical assistance to the agricultural sector of the Municipality of Makato with due consideration on the following:

Complete member’s personal data of members including among others: the financial capacity, family members and the land area as owner or tenant;

The total number of the farmers’ association categorized as to owner, tenant or rented/lessee and area covered;

The objectives/ purposes of the assistance;

The expected outputs from the beneficiaries;

The manner of distribution to bonafide associations or peoples’ organizations duly accredited by the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan of the Municipality of Makato;

The responsibilities of the beneficiary association; and

The regular monitoring of the Municipal Agriculturist Office to avoid duplication or favoritism in the grant of benefits.

We also recommended that the Office of the Municipal Agriculturist keeps record and documents pertinent to its programs and projects to avoid pinpointing of responsibilities and difficulty in the validation of the programs and projects.

